<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: CLOUDS TO CLEAR, LEAVING SUNNY WEEKEND SKIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD and TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The storm clouds that dropped more than an inch of rain on parts of Ventura 
County this week are expected to clear today, leaving sunny skies that should 
last throughout the weekend, forecasters said. 
</P>
<P>
 Daytime temperatures are predicted to stay in the 70s, with evening 
temperatures falling into the 40s and 50s. 
</P>
<P>
 The first storm of the season, which moved in early Monday and lingered 
through Wednesday morning, saturated the mountains north of Ojai with nearly 
three inches of rain. 
</P>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks received 0.67 of an inch of rain during the two-day storm, the 
government center in Ventura recorded 0.35 of an inch, and Ojai and Fillmore 
each received more than an inch of rain. 
</P>
<P>
 Forecasters said at least one another similar storm system should move through 
Ventura County this month. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are pretty much into the fall system," said Stuart Seto, a weather 
specialist with the National Weather Service in Oxnard. "We will probably see 
temperatures getting cooler and the chance of rain increasing. From now on, 
every three or four days, we will see fronts coming in." 
</P>
<P>
 An Oak View woman was killed when her car skidded off a rain-slicked road 
north of Ojai and plummeted about 300 feet down a ravine Tuesday afternoon. She 
was identified Wednesday as Vicki Ann Small, 43. 
</P>
<P>
 Small was intoxicated and not wearing a seat belt when she lost control of her 
car on a curve on California 33, the California Highway Patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
 Small, who was married with two children, was pronounced dead at 6:13 p.m. at 
Ventura County Medical Center, where she had been taken by helicopter after 
firefighters reached her about 50 feet down an embankment beside the road. 
</P>
<P>
 The storm also caused about a dozen minor accidents, but no road closures or 
serious flooding, CHP officials said Wednesday. County Rainfall Here are 
rainfall figures from the Ventura County Flood Control Department for the 
48-hour period ending 6 p.m. Wednesday. Oct. 1 is the beginning of the official 
rain year. 04,22,15,14,17 Rainfall Rainfall Normal rainfall Location last 48 
hours since Oct. 1 to date Camarillo 0.35 0.35 0.06 Casitas Dam n/a n/a 0.07 El 
Rio n/a n/a 0.05 Fillmore 1.14 1.14 0.06 Moorpark 0.39 0.39 0.05 Ojai 1.02 1.02 
0.07 Upper Ojai 1.10 1.10 0.07 Oxnard n/a n/a 0.04 Piru 0.91 0.91 0.06 Santa 
Paula n/a n/a 0.06 Simi Valley 0.16 0.16 0.05 Thousand Oaks 0.67 0.67 0.04 
Ventura Govt. Center 0.35 0.35 0.05 TRACY WILSON 
</P>
